ere—not just for individuals but for the larger society and economy. Dropouts never catch up with high school graduates on any measure. They are less likely to find work at all, and more likely to live in poverty, commit crimes, and suffer health problems. Even life expectancy for dropouts is shorter by seven years than for those who earn a diploma.Rumberger advocates targeting the most vulnerable students as far back as the early elementary grades. And he levels sharp criticism at the conventional definition of success as readiness for college. He argues that high schools must offer all students what they need to succeed in the workplace and independent adult life. A more flexible and practical definition of achievement—one in which a high school education does not simply qualify you for more school—can make school make sense to young people. And maybe keep them there.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aHigh school dropoutszUnited StatesxPrevention. 0aHigh school dropoutszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2011z9783110261189oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2011z978311026123308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET LINGUISTIK UND LITERATURWISSENSCHAFT  2011z9783110261240oZDB-23-DGA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406316740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674063167423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674063167/original  a978-3-1